Lilly Bloomfield
Individual contribution:


The main idea of our Project is that every Barbie has a purpose, reflecting both the historical branding of the doll and the broader
cultural messages it communicates. Traditionally, Barbie has been marketed through specific roles such as Doctor Barbie representing
a distinct career or identity. This framework reinforces the notion that women can occupy a wide range of positions in society, aligning
with more progressive ideals of feminism. At the same time, it subtly raises questions about whether identity should be tied so closely
achievement. 

This concept is also echoed in the recent Barbie film starring Margot Robbie, where each Barbie in Barbieland is assigned a clear role and 
functions perfectly. On the surface, this appears to be empowering women to be successful and confident. However, the film also critiques 
this structure by exposing how limiting it can be. If every Barbie must have a purpose, it leaves little room for self-discovery which are 
essential aspects of real human experience. 

To get to the page related to me it requires you to press on the barbie doll which is meant to look like me. This unfortunately does not
work and only works in certain locations all three of us chipped in on this page. 

My Childhood is shown in page 3. This idea becomes even more significant. Young people are often asked what they want to be when they 
grow up, implying that their value lies in a future role rather than present exploration. By incorporating the idea that every barbie has
a purpose, our project highlights both the aspirational and restrictive elements of this mindset. 

My contributions consisted of choosing and editing the style of the front page and creating the design for my personal childhood page. 
We created a design from Canva and used inspiration from the older barbie movies. Using Canva i created the background using drawings 
of stars i made online and a plain pink background. To fit in the theme we copied the colour of main barbie and used that as the background. 
We did this on Canva first as coding this was quite difficult. We added the moving images by layering GIF’s on top of the main image.  

I developed this idea by placing my childhoods memories inside a camera and using it as a central visual metaphor. The camera represents
how memories are captured and then revisited over time. Rather than showing childhood as a single, fixed narrative the images in the camera
highlight moments suggesting that identity is built through the experiences rather than a predetermined role.  

Instead of placing the photos randomly on the screen, I positioned them relative to the camera so that they look like polaroids coming 
out of the photo. My page differs from the other pages where they use translate and rotate functions to scatter the images and mine have
fixed positions using numbers and X,Y functions. 

The choice of an older style camera also reflects nostalgia and links to the vintage aesthetic of barbie media. This reinforces the
connection between past and present, showing how barbie and personal identity evolve over time. Just as barbie has been  rebranded to 
reflect changing ideas of femininity, our understanding of our own childhoods shifts as we grow older.  

By presenting my memories in this way, i challenge the idea that childhoods should lead directly to a defined purpose. instead, the 
camera symbolises exploration and reflection, emphasising that growth is not linear or fixed. This connects to our wider project which
questions expectations that everyone must have a clear role or identity. Ultimately, my design suggests that identity is fluid, shaped 
by moments and memories rather than confined to a single label. 

If i were to complete this project again, I would take movie clips from the barbie movies and find clips from my childhood to relate them.
This would be a good comparison of bringing in the ideas of barbie always having a purpose or function. 

